
<manpage TITLE="heal" SECTNUM=1>
<mansect>NAME 
 <P>heal - Insert or remove Coda failure emulator filters



<mansect>SYNOPSIS<P>
<bf>heal -h</bf> hostname1 port1 <bf>-h</bf> hostname2 port2<P>
<bf>partition -h</bf> hostname1 port1 <bf>-h</bf> hostname2 port2<P>
<bf>slow -h</bf> hostname1 port1 speed1 <bf>-h</bf> hostname2 port2 speed2<P>


<mansect>DESCRIPTION<P>
<bf>Heal, partition,</bf> and <bf>slow</bf> all manipulate the failure emulators
filters.  These commands are simplified front-ends to <em>ttyfcon (1)</em>.

<bf>Heal</bf> removes all of the filters between <em>hostname1</em> and <em>hostname2</em>.

<bf>Partition</bf> inserts filters on both <em>hostname1</em> and <em>hostname2</em> to
simulate a network failure between the two hosts.

<bf>slow</bf> inserts filters on <em>hostname1</em> and <em>hostname2</em> to control the
network speed between the machines.

The command-line options for these commands are:
<descrip>
<tag><bf>-h</bf> <em>hostname</em></tag>Host to insert or remove filters
on.
<P></descrip>

<descrip>
<tag><bf>port</bf></tag>Port to attatch to.  This should be 1363 for a
Coda client and 1361 for a server.
<P></descrip>

<descrip>
<tag><bf>speed</bf></tag>Speed in bits per second
<P></descrip>



